\subsection{Themes Across the Literature}

There are four patterns that are repeated in these papers.

\textit{Gradient boosting on tabular data.}
Uddin et al.~\cite{uddin2025}, Usman et al.~\cite{usman2025}, and Ramaiah et al.~\cite{ramaiah2024} each find XGBoost to compete with or better than deep networks on structured URL feature sets. The probable reason is that hand-crafted URL characteristics, including the number of slashes and the age of the domain, have no spatial or sequential structure, which deep networks are erected to be exploited. Axis-aligned splits are constructed in gradient boosting on personal features and their combinations, which is the more perfect match of this type of data.

\textit{Class imbalance is very much observed but seldom rectified.}
Tang \& Mahmoud~\cite{tang2021} flag it as one of the two largest open problems in the field in 50 or more reviewed papers. Setiadi et al.~\cite{setiadi2025} and Ramaiah et al.~\cite{ramaiah2024} both demonstrate significant increases in recall after a single occasion balancing is applied. Nonetheless, the majority of papers, such as the base paper, train on raw distributions.

\textit{SHAP represents the tabular cybersecurity XAI standard.}
Capuano et al.~\cite{capuano2022} do this by axiomatic analysis. According to Roy et al.~\cite{roy2024}, SHAP explanations increase analyst acceptance rates. LIME is not uncommon but not able to satisfy the same theoretical assurances.

\textit{Single-dataset evaluation is still the norm.}
Mia et al.~\cite{mia2024} and Hannousse \& Yahiouche~\cite{hannousse2021} both demonstrate that accuracy changes substantially across datasets. But the majority of papers, among them the base paper, report results on only one.


\section{Research Gaps}
\label{sec:gaps}
Nayak et al.~\cite{nayak2025} and five gaps are specific to it. The above-reviewed literature forms the basis of their grounding. Each gap has a remedy in the suggested methodology.

\subsection{Gap 1 --- Class Imbalance Unaddressed}

The Mendeley data employed in the original article is divided into approximately 60 percent genuine URLs to 40 percent phishing. This imbalance is fed directly into training without any correction.

At the times when a model is maximizing the accuracy on imbalanced data, it gets to know that it is safe to bet on the majority class. In phishing detection, most of the categories are legitimate ones. The model develops a bias on clearing URLs that are supposed to be flagged. The outcome is an increased false-negative rate than the underlying data warrants. Practically, a false negative means a user does not get a warning before providing credentials to a fake page.

Alazaidah et al.~\cite{alazaidah2024} record this bias as statistical evidence on similar datasets. Ramaiah et al.~\cite{ramaiah2024} implement SMOTE with this very Mendeley dataset and provide accuracy increasing to about 97.7 per cent, and an even greater gain in recall. Setiadi et al.~\cite{setiadi2025} and Tang \& Mahmoud~\cite{tang2021} verify the trend in other dataset settings.

\noindent\textbf{Fix proposal:} SMOTE the training part alone, and prior to any model fitting. The test partition is left with the original distribution to maintain a disinterested judgment.

\subsection{Gap 2 --- No Feature-Level Explanations}

The four models of the base paper all produce a binary label with nothing else. The score on anti-phishing presented by Nayak et al.\ is a weighted error measure: it favors false negatives in proportion to the total number of them. It measures how wrong the model was, not why it took a certain decision.

This matters operationally. A SOC analyst provided with a phishing alert must be aware of what feature was used to cause the alert. In the absence of that, the analyst may not be able to check the prediction. The decision to the stakeholders cannot be explained by other threat data, and they cannot believe the output to act on it. GDPR Article 22 also provides that automated decisions that have an impact on individuals be describable at will, which a binary label cannot do.

Capuano et al.~\cite{capuano2022} overview XAI for cybersecurity and make SHAP the theoretically good alternative in the case of tabular classifiers, consistency, local accuracy, and the dummy property. Roy et al.~\cite{roy2024} show that SHAP-backed predictions are responded to by analysts more often than unexplained labels. Shafin~\cite{shafin2025} goes on to indicate that SHAP-directed feature selection enhances accuracy in addition to interpretability.

\noindent\textbf{Fix proposal:} Incorporate SHAP TreeExplainer upon pre-integration authority to produce both global feature importances summaries and per-instance explanations of the waterfall.

\subsection{Gap 3 --- Individual Deep Learning Models on Tabular Data}

The four architectures that are trained and evaluated in the base paper act independently. None of them are ensemble techniques and none of them is designed specifically with hand-crafted tabular features.

Deep learning works well when features are spatially correlated or have a sequential structure, which may be an image or text, since it can learn hierarchical representations. The 14 URL features utilized in the base paper are discrete numerical statistics: counts of specific characters, age of domain in days, URL length. There is no pecking order to study. Gradient boosting, in its turn, builds trees one by one with every tree correcting the mistakes of the previous one, producing decision boundaries that are well-adapted to such characteristics.

Each of the studies by Uddin et al.~\cite{uddin2025} or Usman et al.~\cite{usman2025} finds XGBoost beating or matching deep networks on similar feature sets. Kondaiah et al.~\cite{kondaiah2024} validate the fact that ensemble methods compete with single classifiers twenty percent better on phishing tasks.

\noindent\textbf{Fix suggestion:} Replace the four independent deep learning models with XGBoost, which is optimized by GridSearchCV with a 5-fold stratified cross-validation score on F1.

\subsection{Gap 4 --- Univariate Assessment}

The base paper only tests using the Mendeley dataset. This leaves it incompetent to evaluate whether the reported accuracy of 94.46\% is a true generalizable model or one which is most suitable to this specific data collection.

The phishing URLs are time and location sensitive upon collection. Mia et al.~\cite{mia2024} use XGBoost + SHAP on two different datasets and find that SHAP importance rankings shift significantly among them, meaning the decision logic is not necessarily transferable. Hannousse \& Yahiouche~\cite{hannousse2021} compare the same models on UCI, PhishTank, and ISCX and see error variations of 8 percent on the same configurations. The performance of XGBoost is reported by Usman et al.~\cite{usman2025} ranging between 95.58\% and 99.60\% across four datasets.

\noindent\textbf{Proposed fix:} Evaluate on the UCI Phishing Websites Dataset~\cite{uci_phishing} (11,055 URLs, 30 features) as a secondary benchmark alongside the main Mendeley dataset.

\subsection{Gap 5 --- No Discussion on Deployment}

The fundamental paper terminates with the evaluation offline and does not address inference latency, memory footprint, model staleness, or integration pathways.

To be effective in the production of phishing detection, the model needs to rank a URL within a couple of milliseconds. A browser extension running at 500ms per URL is unusable. Beyond latency, Ejaz et al.~\cite{ejaz2023} demonstrate that fixed phishing detectors become unmeasurably less accurate within months as attackers learn to be familiar with known features. Effective obsolescence is discovered by patterns, and Brezeanu et al.~\cite{brezeanu2025} note models fail without retraining within 3--6 months. An article that concludes with offline accuracy leaves such questions completely open.

\noindent\textbf{Proposed solution:} Define concrete deployment use cases, report XGBoost inference latency tests, and describe a retraining schedule.

\section{Proposed Methodology}
\label{sec:method}
\subsection{Overview}

PhishXplain is a three-stage pipeline applied to the same 14-feature
representation used in the base paper, so the results remain directly
comparable.
Stage 1 corrects class imbalance with SMOTE before any model sees the
training data.
Stage 2 fits XGBoost, tuned via GridSearchCV, as the classifier.
Stage 3 runs SHAP TreeExplainer after each prediction to produce
feature attributions.

The design principle is to change the minimum necessary to address each gap.
Feature selection, the 80/20 stratified split, and the evaluation metrics
all match the base paper exactly.

\subsection{Stage 1: SMOTE Class Balancing}

SMOTE~\cite{chawla2002} generates synthetic phishing samples by interpolating
in feature space between real minority-class instances.
For each phishing sample $\mathbf{x}_i$, it selects a random neighbor
$\hat{\mathbf{x}}$ from its $k$ nearest phishing neighbors and creates:

\begin{equation}
  \mathbf{x}_{\text{new}}
    = \mathbf{x}_i + \lambda(\hat{\mathbf{x}} - \mathbf{x}_i),
  \quad \lambda \sim \mathcal{U}(0,1)
  \label{eq:smote}
\end{equation}

We use $k = 5$ and \texttt{random\_state = 42}.
SMOTE runs only on the training partition.
The test partition is left with the original 60/40 distribution to preserve
a realistic evaluation.
This prevents the synthetic samples from influencing any performance metric.

\subsection{Stage 2: XGBoost with GridSearchCV}

XGBoost~\cite{chen2016} minimizes a regularized additive objective over
$K$ trees:

\begin{equation}
  \mathcal{L}(\phi)
    = \sum_{i=1}^{N} l(\hat{y}_i, y_i)
    + \sum_{k=1}^{K}
      \bigl[\gamma T_k + \tfrac{1}{2}\lambda\|\mathbf{w}_k\|^2\bigr]
  \label{eq:xgb}
\end{equation}

where $l$ is binary cross-entropy, $T_k$ is the number of leaves in tree $k$,
and $\mathbf{w}_k$ is the vector of leaf weights.
At boosting round $t$, the ensemble output updates as:

\begin{equation}
  \hat{y}_i^{(t)} = \hat{y}_i^{(t-1)} + f_t(\mathbf{x}_i)
\end{equation}

The closed-form optimal leaf weight for leaf $j$ is:

\begin{equation}
  w_j^* = -\frac{\sum_{i \in I_j} g_i}{\sum_{i \in I_j} h_i + \lambda}
\end{equation}

where $g_i$ and $h_i$ are the first- and second-order gradients of the
loss with respect to the previous round's prediction.

Table~\ref{tab:hparams} lists the hyperparameter grid.
GridSearchCV scores on $F_1$ rather than accuracy to avoid the same
majority-class bias that affects the base paper's training.

