\subsection{Why XGBoost on This Dataset}

The 14 selected URL features are numerical counts and time durations with no
spatial or sequential relationships.
Deep networks can represent these patterns, but they do so through matrix
operations that require more data and more tuning to converge on simple
feature thresholds.
XGBoost learns axis-aligned splits on individual features and their pairwise
interactions, which is precisely what distinguishes phishing from legitimate
URLs in this feature space.

This is not a general claim about XGBoost vs.\ deep learning.
It is specific to hand-crafted tabular features on a dataset of this size.
Uddin et al.~\cite{uddin2025} reach the same conclusion independently on
a different phishing dataset; Ramaiah et al.~\cite{ramaiah2024} confirm it
on this exact Mendeley dataset.

\subsection{Why SMOTE Drives Most of the Recall Gain}

The base paper's recall of 0.944 is not evidence that the model learned
phishing well.
It is evidence that the model learned the majority class well and still
caught most phishing by proximity to legitimate URL patterns.
Once SMOTE populates the minority-class region with additional synthetic
examples, the learned decision boundary moves.
Phishing URLs that previously sat just inside the ``legitimate'' region,
because the model had too few examples to carve out a proper boundary,
are now correctly classified.

The mechanism is straightforward: more phishing training examples close to
the decision boundary force the classifier to make finer distinctions there.
That is why the recall gain (0.944 to 0.972) is larger than the accuracy
gain (94.46\% to 97.18\%) --- recall was the metric most harmed by
the original imbalance.

\subsection{What SHAP Adds to the Design}

SHAP does not change any number in the performance table.
It runs after prediction and does not modify model weights or outputs.

What it changes is the operational status of the system.
A binary label says ``this is phishing.''
SHAP's waterfall output says ``this is phishing because the domain was
registered 1 day ago (+0.31), the URL contains 6 slashes (+0.24),
and the URL length is 67 characters (+0.18).''
A SOC analyst can verify each of those claims against other data sources
in under a minute.
Without SHAP, verification requires manual feature extraction and model
re-interrogation, which is not practical at scale.

The same explanations enable GDPR compliance for any automated decision
that affects an identifiable user, which blacklist systems and the base
paper's models cannot provide.

\subsection{Improvement in Experimental Design}

Beyond individual technical changes, PhishXplain improves on the base
paper's experimental design in two ways.

First, the primary metric during hyperparameter tuning is $F_1$ rather than
accuracy.
This means the model is optimized for a balance between precision and recall
from the outset, rather than being tuned for a metric that rewards
majority-class predictions.

Second, secondary dataset evaluation on the UCI Phishing
Dataset~\cite{uci_phishing} provides a generalization check.
A result of 96.4\% on UCI, using a model trained entirely on Mendeley data,
is not a guarantee of universal generalization, but it is stronger evidence
of robustness than a single-dataset result can provide.

\section{Results and Findings}
\label{sec:results}
The proposed PhishXplain methodology was evaluated on the UCI Phishing Websites dataset to address the generalization gap identified in the base paper. The evaluation utilized the same 80/20 train-test split strategy. The results demonstrate the efficacy of the proposed pipeline, especially the integration of SMOTE and XGBoost with GridSearchCV.

\subsection{Performance Metrics}
Table~\ref{tab:results} presents the quantitative metrics achieved by our proposed model. The integration of SMOTE prior to XGBoost training successfully compensated for class imbalance, achieving an overall Accuracy of 96.56\% and a Recall of 96.22\%. The high F1-score (96.13\%) and AUC (99.51\%) indicate that the model maintains a strong balance between precision and recall, minimizing false negatives which are critical in cybersecurity.

